title: 2020 New York State Senate election
added: == Background ==
{{Main|2018 New York State Senate election}}

In the 2018 election the Democratic Party won a majority of seat with 39 of the 63 seats in the New York State Senate, gaining 8 seats from the Republicans. The Republican Party won 23 seats becoming the minority in the State Senate for the first time since 2010. [[Simcha Felder]] was the only Democratic who continued to caucus with the Republicans.

title: 2020 New York State Senate election
added: As of December 3, 2020, unofficial election night results from the New York State Senate elections were available on the website of the New York State Board of Elections. That website notes that county boards of elections "received a historically high number of absentee ballots for the November 3rd 2020 General Election due to the coronavirus pandemic", and adds that "Unofficial election night results do not include the results of absentee ballot voting".<ref>{{Cite web|title=NYS Board of Elections Unofficial Election Night Results|url=https://nyenr.elections.ny.gov/|access-date=2020-12-03|website=nyenr.elections.ny.gov}}</ref> On Election Day, City & State New York reported that "in many of the state’s most competitive Senate races, Republicans have managed to preliminarily come out on top"; however, City & State cautioned that "outstanding absentee ballots meant that the status of many races remained uncertain and could very well turn around for candidates on both sides of the aisle who found themselves behind on election night. Those mail-in ballots were obviously the major caveat in every race, which will likely drag out many results for a week or more".<ref>https://www.cityandstateny.com/articles/politics/campaigns-elections/2020-new-york-state-legislative-general-election-results.html</ref>

On November 23, 2020, Spectrum News reported that Senate Democrats had won at least 41 seats, and added that races in Senate Districts 40, 42, and 50 had not yet been called.<ref>https://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/central-ny/politics/2020/11/24/-a-historic-supermajority----nys-senate-democrats-declare-victory</ref> In Senate District 40, Republican Senate candidate Rob Astorino conceded the race to Democratic incumbent Pete Harckham.<ref>https://westchester.news12.com/harckham-wins-re-election-in-th-state-senate-district-as-astorino-concedes</ref> In Senate District 42, Democratic incumbent Jen Metzger conceded the race to Republican challenger Mike Martucci.<ref>https://legislativegazette.com/14930-2/</ref><ref>https://www.wvdispatch.com/2020/11/new-york-state-senator-jen-metzger-concedes-42nd-senate-district-race/</ref>

The 2020 New York State Senate election results are scheduled to be certified on December 7, 2020.<ref>https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/law/2020GenElecPoliticalCalendar.pdf</ref><ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/when-do-states-certify-election-results/</ref>
